<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NAME CALLING: Former Assemblyman Tom McClintock (R-Thousand Oaks) is accusing 
acting Secretary of State Tony Miller of using his duties "as a partisan 
sledgehammer to harass Republicans." He even suggested the governor should 
replace him. . . . What was the heinous crime? Miller denied McClintock's 
request to be called "taxpayer advocate" on the ballot in the race for state 
controller. The ballot designation is supposed to reflect a candidate's 
principal profession, and Miller routinely rejects "taxpayer advocate," except 
for tax lawyers. McClintock, who now works for an anti-tax group, vows to sue. 
</P>
<P>
 HUNGRY FOR ATTENTION: For 19 days, the founder of a fringe political party has 
refused food served at the Ventura County Jail in an ongoing protest over what 
he perceives as government atrocities. . . . Christopher McGrath, 41, the 
founder of the Rock 'n' Roll Party in Simi Valley, goes to trial today on 
trespass charges for holding solitary sit-ins at the Simi Valley courthouse. . 
. . The jail's medical staff checks him daily, said Cmdr. Ken Kipp. "His weight 
is down to 172 pounds, a drop of seven or eight pounds." 
</P>
<P>
 SIDEWALK BUSTERS: Towering trees provide shade, please the eye, and add to the 
value of any home. But some trees, particularly exotic varieties from overseas, 
can be a tremendous nuisance in the city (Ventura County Life, Page 24). . . . 
They bore into sewer lines, create fire hazards, buckle pavement. One of the 
most troublesome is the Indian laurel, described by one arborist as "our No. 1 
concrete buster." 
</P>
<P>
 AND THEY'RE OFF: The off-track betting facility at the Ventura County 
Fairgrounds has corralled world champion jockey Johnny Longden as a treat for 
longtime horse racing fans from 11 a.m. to noon tomorrow. . . . Now 87, Longden 
retired in 1966 as history's winningest race-rider with 6,032 victories. He led 
most of his 32,000 races and other jockeys joked they didn't know what he 
looked like from the front. "Pound for pound, he was the greatest athlete that 
ever lived," said historian Biff Lowry. 
</P>
