<HEADLINE>
<P>
NHL ROUNDUP; ESSENSA STILL NOT THE ANSWER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Detroit Red Wings were just a player short, and they got him -- goaltender 
Bob Essensa -- in a trade with the Winnipeg Jets on March 8. 
</P>
<P>
 He has lost four games since, including a 5-4 decision at Ottawa on Wednesday 
in which he faced only 15 shots. 
</P>
<P>
 Rookie Alexei Yashin completed a three-goal Senator comeback that brought 
victory in the Senators' first game home since an 18-day trip in which they 
lost seven of eight games and were outscored, 44-11. 
</P>
<P>
 The Red Wings fell a point behind Toronto for first place in the NHL's Western 
Conference by losing to the league's worst team. It was only the 12th victory 
in 74 games for Ottawa, which dressed six new players and at one point had four 
of them on the ice at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
 Canadian Olympian Derek Mayer scored his first two NHL goals for the Senators. 
</P>
<P>
 Winnipeg 3, Montreal 1 -- Tim Cheveldae, for whom Essensa was traded, ended 
the Canadiens' 11-game unbeaten streak, stopping 39 shots at Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
 Florida 1, Toronto 1 -- Stu Barnes scored a first-period goal at Hamilton, 
Canada, and the Panthers increased their lead over Philadelphia and the New 
York Islanders for the final Eastern Conference playoff spot to four points. 
</P>
<P>
 St. Louis 3, Buffalo 2 -- Curtis Joseph stopped 27 shots and Igor Korolev 
scored the game-winning goal for the Blues at Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
 New York Rangers 5, Edmonton 3 -- Adam Graves set a club record with his 50th 
and 51st goals and Mike Richter made 28 saves for the Rangers at Edmonton. 
</P>
<P>
 Graves broke Vic Hadfield's team record of 50 goals, set in the 1971-72 
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
