<HEADLINE>
<P>
AFTER CRECION BREAKS HIS NOSE, CHAMINADE TAKES ONE ON CHIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRENE GARCIA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Having lost five consecutive games to Notre Dame High, Chaminade could have 
used Adam Crecion, one of its best hitters. 
</P>
<P>
 Crecion, a senior right fielder, broke his nose in the second inning of 
Friday's game against Harvard-Westlake and will be out for the rest of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 Without Crecion, Chaminade could muster only five hits Wednesday in a 7-4 
Mission League defeat to Notre Dame when the Eagles' sixth-inning rally fell 
short. 
</P>
<P>
 Notre Dame (7-1, 3-0 in league play) collected 12 hits and built a five-run 
lead before Chaminade (4-4, 1-2) made its run. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've fallen into this pattern where we fall behind and rely on miraculous 
comebacks at the end," Chaminade Coach Dave Desmond said. "We just can't do 
that." 
</P>
<P>
 With Notre Dame ahead, 6-1, in the sixth, three Chaminade batters went to the 
plate with the bases loaded but couldn't manage a hit. 
</P>
<P>
 Notre Dame starting pitcher Matt Egan (2-0) walked Gabe Crecion to force home 
one run and reliever Juan Montes walked John Gunn to make it 6-3. Montes struck 
out Scot Dey and Scott Shubeck grounded out to end the inning. "They battled 
back and I knew we let up at times," Notre Dame Coach Tom Dill said. "They 
really did a good job." 
</P>
<P>
 After the Knights scored an insurance run in the top of the seventh on Rich 
Igou's home run, they called on Igou to prevent a possible comeback in the 
bottom of the inning. He struck out three and gave up one hit. Chaminade's 
Jason Giovannettone, who walked, scored the game's last run on a throwing 
error. 
</P>
<P>
 Catcher Eddie Romero went two for three with a two-run homer over the 
right-field fence in the third for Notre Dame, which jumped ahead with two runs 
in the first and two in the second. 
</P>
<P>
 Senior Joel Orme (2-2) went the distance and took the loss for the Eagles. He 
went two for four and drove in a run with a double. 
</P>
</TEXT>
