<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLASSIC OF THE WEEK: JACKSON BROWNE, "SATURATE BEFORE USING" (1972), 
ELEKTRA/ASYLUM  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JANET KINOSIAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jackson Browne made his best record on his first try out. From the tender 
"Jamaica Say You Will" to the emotionally hungry "Song for Adam" and the 
radiant, gospel-drenched "Rock Me on the Water," he wrote convincingly of what 
it was to be a young, sensitive man grown up in the '60s, afflicted by 
post-'60s fallout.There is a longing, spiritual undercurrent to his voice, 
accentuated by some of the best studio musicians of the time (Russell Kunkel on 
drums, Leland Sklar on bass, Craig Doerge on piano -- the same group that 
played on most of the James Taylor and Carole King records back then). 
"Saturate's" tone is sparse but warm, Browne's vision deeply intelligent, the 
tempo even; this is the world before '70s glam invaded everything. The focus is 
always clearly on Browne, his guitar and his words. And if that voice singing 
harmony sounds familiar, it's a nice, Woodstock-era sound, too: David Crosby. 
JANET KINOSIAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
